:cron 
/CRon [add..|list|-]    Manipulate the list of cronjobs
Cronjobs are periodically sheduled.
You add a cronjob with "/cron add n m command..", where 'n' is the interval
in minutes, and 'm' specifies how often the given command is executed.
If 'm' is 0, then the job will not expire.
Example: "/cron add 10 3 /invite dl9sau@db0tud" will execute the
invitation command every 10 minutes for 3 times.
With "/cron" or "/cron list" you get a list of the current cron jobs.
You could remove cron job #2 with "/cron delete 2" or "/cron - 2";
with "/cron -" or "/cron delete", the whole crontab is removed.
Note, that the crontab currently is not stored in your /profile.
As operator, you could remove crojobs for other users: "/cron ~ ha1ck -"
will remove the cron table for user ha1ck. If user has more than one
connection, try "/cron ~ ha1ck/1 -", "/cron ~ ha1ck/2 -", etc..
without user/number, number defaults to 1.
