:invite
/Invite user [channel]  Invites named user to this channel.

An invitation to the named user is sent. The invite is passed through all
convers nodes in the net. If the user is on another channel, he will be able
to join your private channel. If he is online on a unix machine, he will
receive the invitation message via standard broadcast by conversd. In the
latter case he will be unable to join a private channel directly.

New: you query for
- "user@host": then this invitation is only sent to this host.
  user@host will respond to, if user is not logged on at host "host" (not
  on old conversd's).
- "user@all" will send the invitation to every host in the network,
  regardless if an invitation somewhere in the way was successfull (useful
  when a user is idle on multible hosts..). you may get multible responses.
both query types may inform you, if the invitation could not be sent (mesg n
for e.g.) (not on old conversd's).

:irc
/IRc                    Toggles between IRC-client / normal convers mode
Be careful if you are already signed on with an irc-client, because
when you issue the /irc command (thus switching to normal convers mode),
this may be a point of no-return.
Tips:
  - if you have a password set, then you could automaticaly switch to
    irc mode by sending PASS yourpass (whis is useful, when your sysop
    forces an automatic /name login by script, where you have no chance
    to send irc-mode NICK / USER login).
  - if you like to send normal convers commands, which mostly still are
    available in irc mode, (for e.g. /online or /who * (because some
    irc-clients do not allow /who with a wildcard)), you may preceed
    your command with '/quote' or '/raw'.
    then your client will send the argument raw to conversd. i.e.
    '/quote online' or '/raw online'. this is an irc-client issue.
    if your irc-client does not support this, don't blame me.
  - You have a classic irc client and own a GNU/linux system, but want to
    go to an irc-mode capable conversd via ax25. well, you could try this:
    add the line
      6668  stream  tcp  nowait  root  /usr/sbin/tcpd  /usr/local/sbin/axconvconnect.sh
    axconvconnect.sh is a shell script:
    #!/bin/sh
    # use the unix ax25 protocol stack
    exec /usr/local/bin/rawconvers  -s  "ax25:db0erf-8,db0bln<dl9sau-8" -i "convers"
    or
    # use wampes' or tnt's command unix-socket
    exec /usr/local/bin/rawconvers  -s  "unix:/tcp/.sockets/netcmd" -i "connect ax25 db0erf-8\nconvers 9876\n/irc"
    cave: if you have not set a password, your login process will not be 
    delayed, and you are 1. on the convers default channel and 2. not in
    irc mode. alternatively, you could add "/irc" to rawconvers args.
    If you give -i "foo\n\10bar", then the line "bar\n" is sent 10sec
    after "foo\n".
    the rawconvers command is part of the conversd package.
    you are encouraged to add the line
      axconvconnect.sh: 0.0.0.0/0.0.0.0 EXCEPT 127.0.0.1, some.other.trusted.host.domain
    to /etc/hosts.deny, and kill -HUP your identd.
    Instead of using indetd, you may use the netcat utility as an easy
    on-demand alternative:
      nc -l -p 6668 -e "axconnnect.sh" localhost &
      irc dl9sau localhost:6668
  - usually, an irc client pings every 30s. this is too much for ampr.
    with xchat, you set "lagometer = 0" in ~/.xchat/xchat.conf (via menu:
    Settings->Setup->Window Layout->Meters->Lag meter->Off)
    An xchat 2.0.x for win$ user changes the variables in
      C:\Documents and Settings\<username>\Application Data\X-Chat 2\xchat.conf
      to "away_size_max = 1" and "gui_lagometer = 0".
  - password issues for BitchX users: some BitchX versions have troubles
    sending the password (conversd answers PASS :Not enough parameters).
    -> imagine your password is "bar". now set your pass in BitchX to
    "foo bar", and everything is fine..
