:links
/LInks [-] [args]       List or setup links (see "help links")

The current link state is displayed. In the standard version, host name,
link state, link round trip times, neighbour revision codes and state time
followed by time of next try and count of connect tries (on disconnected or
connecting links) are shown, connected lines print out their queue length
and total transmit statistics.

If you are sysop, you may also set up or remove links at runtime.
The detailed description below is only interesting for Sysops. 

Adding a link might happen like this:

Old style:
    "/l dc6iq-u 2 4 unix:/tcp/.sockets/netcmd connect tcp dc6iq 3600"
  In this command a host called dc6iq-u will be entered into group 2 by
  quality 4. The link will be established by using WAMPES.
  This is was obsolete quite a while due to the new Primary / Fallback
  Link syntax below.
  Instead, use for now. (dc6iq-u is it's own primary)
    "/l dc6iq-u 2 4 unix:/tcp/.sockets/netcmd dc6iq-u connect tcp dc6iq 3600"

New style (backward compatibility retained - quality and group ignored):
    "/l db0hdf 1 1 db0hdf.ampr.org:3600"                # primary
    "/l db0fc 1 1 db0fc-u.ampr.org:3600 db0hdf"         # fallback for db0hdf
    "/l db0fc 1 1 db0fc-1.ampr.org:3600 db0fc-u"        # fallback for db0fc-u
    "/l db0zwi 1 1 db0zwi.ampr.org:3600"                # another primary
    "/l db0hht 1 1 db0hht.ampr.org:3600 db0hht"         # another primary
    "/l db0bid 1 1 unix:/afu/convers/sockets/socket db0bid connect ax25 db0bid-7" # another primary
    "/l db0lpz 1 1 ax25:db0lpz-10 db0lpz"               # another primary
    "/l db0hdf 1 1 ax25:db0hdf-10 db0lpz foo\nfoo bar"  # fallback for db0lpz

As we see in in the last example, "foo" and "foo bar" is being sent to
db0hdf, after the link is established. this could be used for sending
commands to the link partner for connecting or starting a wrapper to
the remote conversd. This is optional.

TCP port-Numbers may be ommited. Then the default port (we're listening on)
will be used.

Existing entries will be automaticaly deleted.
A note on using unix sockets (unix:/tcp/.sockets/netcmd for
e.g.): for security sake, the path for accessable unix sockets
must be added to conversd.conf: "unix_sockets /tcp/.sockets/"

In the example with db0bid, we use a unix-socket. note that the widely
used linux-packet program "tnt" is capable to understand the wampes connect
command set (but you may not give a list of digipeaters - they have
to be configured in tnt, and only ax25 connections are supported. see
the manual page of tnt for more details).

Not yet implemented:
- netrom:db0nos

If you add an existing link, it will be automaticaly substituted with
the new information.

To remove a link, say:
  "/li - db0fc" removes link to db0fc
  "/li - -"     removes every link in the table
  "/li - all"   removes every link in the table

If you know that a host does loops when he connects, you may block them
manually with "/li ! db0dau" or "/li lock db0dau".
These hosts are shown as "Disc./locked!" (care at the '!' sign) in the
linklist, which indicates that they have been administratively locked.
[An alternative way is to configure an AUTH HOST socket for permlinks,
or to set a password for the misconfigured host: /mkpass new db0dau random]

An existing entry could be queried like this:
  "/li ? db0fc"
  you get additional information.
If you want to get this long list for all hosts,
  "/li long" is the command of your choice - or better, "/l l" ;)
  "static" indicates a permanent link, "learned" means that a new host
  has connected us. For static links, you'll see additional information
  (socket, optional connect command, ..).

With "/link db0fc" you may query the link-list at db0fc.
There are some conversd's around which only respond on "/link @db0fc".
So you should try both variants. This conversd will respond on both
queries.
Some conversd may also answer to a "/link all" request (we, for e.g.).

With the new option "/li <" or "/li acl" you could modify the access list.
You may need this if you set up only user connects ("Access 44.0.0.0/8 USER")
in your conversd.conf, and you add a new link partner in the running conversd
with '/li add ...' and do not want to restart conversd. Syntax is like in the
conversd.conf file: '/li < 44.128.0.1 HOST'. '/li <' shows the current ACL.
Current entries of the acl are not deleted nor substituted. The new entry
has a higher priority than the previous.

Because we are all human, and all this is very cryptic, you could also say
  "/li add db0fc 1 1 db0fc-u.ampr.org:3600 db0hdf" instead of "/li db0fc ..."
  "/li + db0fc 1 1 db0fc-u.ampr.org:3600 db0hdf" instead of "/li db0fc ..."
  "/li drop db0fc 1 1 db0fc-u.ampr.org:3600 db0hdf" instead of "/li - db0fc ..."
  "/li del db0fc 1 1 db0fc-u.ampr.org:3600 db0hdf" instead of "/li - db0fc ..."
  "/li lookup db0fc" instead of "/li db0fc ..."
  "/li list db0fc" instead of "/li long db0fc"
  "/li reset db0fc" will reset the link to db0fc.
  "/li kill db0fc"  will reset the link to db0fc.
  "/li ~ db0fc"     will reset the link to db0fc.
  "/li ~ all"       will reset every link in the table.
  "/li reset db0fc because this reason" will reset the link to db0fc,
                    stating "because this reason" as reason.
  "/li lock db0fc"  will lock the link to db0fc for (default) 30 minutes.
  "/li ! db0fc"     will lock the link to db0fc for (default) 30 minutes.
  "/li lock db0fc some reason" will lock the link to db0fc for (default) 30
                    minutes, stating "some reason" as reason.
  "/li lock db0fc 60" will lock the link to db0fc for 60 minutes.
  "/li lock db0fc 60 some reason" will lock the link to db0fc for 60 minutes,
                    stating "some reason" as reason.
  add, drop, del, acl ..  could be abbreviated.

In irc-client mode the /link command ist reseverd otherwise, but you
may access this feature by issuing the "/clink" command.

