:note
/NOTE [text]            Set personal description (please use /PErs instead)
:notify
/Notify [calls]         Send notice if one of calls signs on

You are notified if one person out of the notification list appears on any
channel in this convers. E.g. "/notify + dc1ik" adds the user dc1ik to the
notification list, "/notify - db4ut" removes him from the list. The list is
initially treated as if a plus "+"-sign was given, multiple lists may be
specified. The following command would be legal and would result in adding
dc1ik, db4ut and dg3kcr to the list, while removing dc6iq and dh2paf:
"/notify + dc1ik db4ut - dc6iq dh2paf +dg3kcr"
Removing non-members to the list is ignored.
"/notify @db0tud" will notify you if a new user from the system db0tud will
sign on.
"/notify dl9sau@db0tud" will notify you if dl9sau at system db0tud will
sign on.
"/notify #73" will notify you if someone joins convers channel 73.

In irc-client mode the /notify command ist a program local for the client;
you may access this feature issuing the "/cnotify" command.
:notice
/NOTICe <user|ch> foo.. Sends a notice "foo" to a user or the channel
This is actually an extension to the /me command, and greatly differs from
the /msg command.
:online
/ONline                 Shows who is online (like "/who n")
:operator:sysop
/OPerator [number]      Become operator
:paclen
/PAclen [n]             Set / view current packet length

With this command, you are able to improve your throughput according to
your link reliability and capacity.
For e.g., with n = 120 the transmitted packets will contain 120 bytes data.
With n = 0, the paclen is switched back to the default. Without n, you'll
get the current setting.
:personal
/PErsonal [text]        Set personal description

A brief description can be set up, accessible to all users via the "/who"
command. A typical Message looks like this: "/pers Fred, Buechig, JN49fb".
This text is saved by the Server for future connects.
:prompt
/PRompt abcd            Prompts a=query b=std c=ctrl-g d=ctrl-h

The prompt command takes up to four arguments in one concatenated string.
Thus "/prompt abcd" will set up "a" for the query prompt, "b" for the
standard prompt. "d" is the character to remove the prompt, and "c" is
displayed whenever a text is sent to you. Normally you make "c" a control-G
(beep char) and "d" a backspace or delete character (control-h or 0x7f).
With "/prompt", "/prompt -", or "/prompt off" prompting is reseted.
:profile
/PROFile [command ..]   add / run / list / delete profile

The profile is executed everytime you log into convers.
The current profile is stored on the server.
You could add / remove / change a command to your profile with
  /profile add /who q
  /profile del /who
If you add an existing command, the old command will be substituted.

You could delete your profile with "/profile del".
"+" is aequvivalent to add, "-" to del, "!" to run.
help or ? shows short usage.

View your current profile with /profile (or /profile list)

You can re-run your current profile with /profile run (or /profile !).

Note that some commands automaticaly make changes to your profile.
Actually, theres commands are:
  /charset, /language, /notify, /filter, /filtermsgs
  /width, /paclen, /idle, /beep, /prompt, /timestamp,
  /trigger, /shownicks

As operater you may list / add / delete / run other user's profile,
for example for reparation of misconfigurations.
How to list dl9sau's profile:
  /profile ~dl9sau list
:query
/QUEry [user]           Start/End a private conversation

The username given as argument will be the only recipient for all further
texts. They are send as private messages (just like /m). With no optional
argument, this mode is left, and received lines will again appear on your
current channel.
:bye:exit:quit
/Quit [arg]             Terminate the convers session

Passing this command to conversd, you will retire from the famous Ping-Pong
conversation. I hope you enjoyed this stuff :-)
If you say "/quit foo bar", foo bar is sent as a reason text.
#:quote
#/QUOte                  Sends host's Quote-of-the-day to the current channel
#
#Sends host's Quote-of-the-day to the current channel.
:realnames
/Realnames [user]       List nicknames and realnames of users

List nicknames and realnames of users (same as "/who r").
:restart
/REStart                Restart the convers server - operator-only command

This is a operator mode command that brings down all active links and users.
The server remains up and active after the /restart command is complete.
This is good to flush the system and start fresh, without requiring the
server to exit.
#:roll
#/ROll                   Simulates the rolling of two dice/displays selection
#
#Simulates the rolling of two dice and displays selected dice.
:rtt
/RTt [time]             Test link time between you and this conversd

Type "/rtt" and respond with the proposed "/rtt time" line.
In most cases, this will be done by your packet program automaticaly ;)
Note: //rtt will work, too.
:msg:send:write
/Send user text         Send a private message to user
:shownicks
/SHownicks [status]     Toggles the nickname feature (or shows current status)
If you dislike the nickname extension, you can use the shownicks
command. Then, when users with nicknames write, you only see their
real name.
With "/SHownicks status" you get the current setting, without changing it.
Currently, this command is not available in ircmode.
#:smiley
#/SMiley                 Displays a random 'smiley' and its meaning
#
#Displays a random 'smiley' and the meaning of that smiley.
:stats
/STats [[mode] [num]]   Request statistics on this server
:operator:sysop:/priv
/SYsOp [number]         Become operator

Invoking this command, a random number from 0..99999 will be displyed.
Take each digit, multiply with the corresponding digit in the secret number
at the configuration file, sum it and enter the number by invoking
"/oper <n>".
You may also use more modern algorithms with "/sys md5" or "/sys sys"
as described in the /auth section.
A SecretPass configuration is recommendet; the numeric variant is used
as fallback if SecretPass is not defined.
:sysinfo
/SYSinfo [host]         Requests information about a specific host site

Requests system information about a specific host. The information can
contain anything, but should at least contain the email address of the
sysop of that site.
If you ask for host "all", then you'll receive SYsinfo messages from
every connected host.
#:/priv
#//priv [number]         Become operator (use /oper instead)
:time
/TIme                   Sends host's current time

Sends host's current time
:timestamp
/TIMEStamp              Toggles time information on channel and user msgs

When timestamping is on, channel and user msgs will be marked with
a time stamp. The /Timestamp command has no argument (it toggles the
state). The current state is stored in your /profile. This command is
not available in IRC-mode, since most irc-client implementations have
this feature by their own.
:topic
/TOpic [#chan] [text]   Set channel topic. Text=@ removes topic

A brief description of the channel topic can be set. Other users can look
it up with the "/who quick" or "/list" commands. If the channel number is
omitted, the topic will be set to the current channel, else to the desired
one. if no #channel is given, the topic will appear on the current channel,
if specified, the topic on that channel will be set (only if you're logged
on to that channel). To clear a topic, just try to set a topic like "@" :-)
An empty topic command diplays the current's channel topic.

"/Topic #all" prints all topics of all channels, if a topic is set.
Same as "/who t".
:trigger
/TRigger [n|off]        Set / Show / Switch off Anti-Idle timer
Using /trigger command, a line to you is sent if for n minutes no data
has been sent to or received by you. This prevents you on silent channels
from being disconnected by some digipeaters.
Example:
  /trigger 60  will send the message every hour
  /trigger -10 is special: will send every ten minutes a blank (or in
               irc-mode a newline) instead of the informational text
  /trigger off will switch trigger timer off
  /trigger     will show the current state of the timer (but consider that
               the timers will be reseted)
:users
/USers [[*|#][channel]|A|C|L|N|Q|R|S|T|U users|@ node]  List users and their channel numbers

Alias to /who. Type /help who for more information
:uptime
/UPtime                 How long has this conversd been up ?

The uptime command tells us how long this conversd is up and running.

:wall:
/WAll <message>         Write message to all local users

Wall writes a message to all local users. It's a operator-only command.
:who:
/Who  [[*|#][channel]|A|C|L|N|Q|R|S|T|U users|@ node]  List users and their channel numbers

The who command supports up to four switches. An "a" will diplay all users
and their Away texts, if set. A "l" generates a _long_ list containing
personal texts, away texts and Queue informations. A "q" gives a brief list.
A "s" gives a more brief list (without topic).
An asterisk "*" displays the users on your current channel in normal mode.
With "/Who * 99" you get all users at channel 99, in the "/who n" format.
For irc friends: "/who #99" is now a synonym to /who * 99".
An 'r' lists users with Nicknames & Personal info.
An 'n' lists user / host / via, channel, personal text, and if away. This
is actualy what the /online command does.
An 't' lists all topics on all channels, if set. Same as "/topic #all".
If you want to get informations about specific users, you can use the
"who u userlist" variant or the "whois user" command.
With "@ node" you'll get a list of current users coming from a given node.
With "@ " you'll get a list of current users coming from the local node.
:whois
/WHOIs user             Gives complete information about a user

This is a question to conversd. "/whois dc6iq" will show all available
informations about dc6iq, i.e. joined channels, personal description,
away message and times.
Whois compares also the "nickname".
Wildcards are allowd. You may say "/whois dl*", or "/whois *foo*".
Note that Whois "*" will print detailed information on every user, which
will be a very long list..
:width
/WIdth [value]          Set/show terminal width

Tell conversd about your screen width. Then formatted messages will use the
entire screen. It is set to 80 by default. A value of 0 sets the screen
to unlimited linelength with unformated output (no word wrap, blanks will be
kept). "/width reset" resets the screen width to default.

:wizard:zap
/WIZard [xxx]           Sysop command: Manually send conversd protokol packets

This command will send packets in conversd protocol to our neighbours.
Be very careful. You not only need to be a sysop, but also a protocol wizard ;)
:msg:send:write
/WRite user text        Send a private message to user

Send a text to one special user or a joined channel. If the message should
be redirected to a channel, The command must be invoked in this syntax:
"/msg #<channel> <text>". The adressee (if user) can indicate the private
character of the message due to additional asterisks in his received lines.
a mesage written by dc6iq to dc1ik looks like this: "/m dc1ik This is a Test"
will be received by dc1ik like this: "<*dc6iq*>: This is a test".

:verbose
/Verbose                Toggles verbose Flag

The verbose flag is toggled. You will be flooded with information if you
enable this feature.
:version
/VERSion                Show version information

Print out version information to this software.

:/COMP
 //COMP [on|off]      Switch on/off or show current compression state

The compression algorithm is the standard lzw compression used in ampr,
which most ampr programs could handle properly.
Note that it does not work well on non-standard ascii characters.
Compression may not work if you connected to convers via telnet, unix
(axspawn) or the conversd session is handled by tnt (if tnt is not set
up providing //comp by itself). In doubt, ask your sysop.
